WEBVTT

00:06.316 --> 00:09.009
[ Wolf howling,
animals calling ]

00:15.429 --> 00:18.984
Narrator:
Previously on "Mountain Men"...

00:19.019 --> 00:21.538
-My God, we got one. We got one.
-[ Laughs ]

00:21.573 --> 00:23.713
...Tom strikes pay dirt...

00:23.747 --> 00:25.956
Tom: That's what they call
trapping beaver.

00:25.991 --> 00:27.993
Sean: Beaver fever.

00:28.028 --> 00:29.891
...Marty takes a major hit...

00:29.926 --> 00:32.894
Marty: I'm way behind where
I thought I was gonna be.

00:32.929 --> 00:35.380
Narrator: ...but a discovery
puts him back in the game...

00:35.414 --> 00:36.519
Marty: What do you think
those are?

00:36.553 --> 00:38.314
Wolf?
Yeah.

00:38.348 --> 00:43.319
...Eustace finally gets rolling
after the storm...

00:43.353 --> 00:45.010
-Yeah!
-We're back in business.

00:45.045 --> 00:47.185
Eustace: Now that we've got
the wagon wheel fixed,

00:47.219 --> 00:49.083
we can get those logs.

00:49.118 --> 00:52.742
Narrator: ...and in Alaska,
Morgan goes into survival mode

00:52.776 --> 00:55.331
to fight the freeze.

00:55.365 --> 00:58.506
Morgan: We're a couple of weeks
into winter proper now,

00:58.541 --> 01:00.370
and there's an endless list

01:00.405 --> 01:02.993
of projects to do around here.

01:03.028 --> 01:13.073
♪♪

01:13.073 --> 01:25.913
♪♪

01:25.947 --> 01:29.158
Narrator: 200 miles south
of the Arctic Circle,

01:29.192 --> 01:31.850
mid-winter transforms
the Great Alaska Range

01:31.884 --> 01:35.543
into one of the most
hostile places on earth.

01:35.578 --> 01:38.028
With daylight lasting less
than 5 hours

01:38.063 --> 01:40.203
and temperatures
holding around 40 below,

01:40.238 --> 01:44.311
life here will be
a constant battle for survival

01:44.345 --> 01:48.211
until the spring thaw
arrives.

01:48.246 --> 01:51.835
Morgan Beasley is prepared
to endure the lean times.

01:51.870 --> 01:54.010
He's stocked up on dry food
and horse feed

01:54.044 --> 01:55.598
to last several months,

01:55.632 --> 01:57.669
but he and his partner
Margaret rely on hunting

01:57.703 --> 02:00.706
and trapping for the bulk
of their protein.

02:00.741 --> 02:02.777
Morgan: Need to be thinking
about the months ahead,

02:02.812 --> 02:05.573
so we're establishing
this new trapline

02:05.608 --> 02:07.920
that we hope to use for years.

02:07.955 --> 02:09.819
Narrator:
Morgan is a rookie trapper,

02:09.853 --> 02:12.753
but Margaret brings 2 years
of experience to the table

02:12.787 --> 02:15.928
along with a large collection
of trapping gear.

02:15.963 --> 02:19.173
Morgan:
Margaret and I I think make a
pretty darn good team out here,

02:19.208 --> 02:22.901
and harvesting these furbearers
is gonna provide

02:22.935 --> 02:25.075
a need for us
in terms of food

02:25.110 --> 02:27.250
and warm winter clothing.

02:27.285 --> 02:30.011
So I'm gonna get
onto the beaver trapping,

02:30.046 --> 02:32.393
and set a few more marked traps

02:32.428 --> 02:34.533
and see what's out there.

02:34.568 --> 02:36.846
Ready?
Oh, yeah.
We got boilage.

02:36.880 --> 02:37.985
Nice.

02:38.019 --> 02:40.367
We're gonna dip the traps
in hot water

02:40.401 --> 02:43.335
and then hang them in the steam
to get rid of its odor

02:43.370 --> 02:46.131
and so hopefully they don't
smell like oil or gas,

02:46.166 --> 02:49.755
help mask any other human scents
a little bit more.

02:49.790 --> 02:52.965
Narrator:
Sterilizing the traps increases
the chances of a catch

02:53.000 --> 02:55.313
if the bait is fresh
and pungent.

02:55.347 --> 02:56.831
Margaret makes a batch
by gutting

02:56.866 --> 02:58.833
and prepping a snowshoe hare.

02:58.868 --> 03:03.044
It'll be using the feet and some
of these kind of scraps.

03:03.079 --> 03:05.357
It might turn pretty
nicely in the breeze.

03:05.392 --> 03:07.359
Feet will as well.

03:10.569 --> 03:13.607
With the trapping, we're
definitely looking to supplement

03:13.641 --> 03:14.987
what we have here.

03:15.022 --> 03:16.748
The food we eat,
the clothes we wear.

03:16.782 --> 03:18.991
And I'm using what
we can find in nature

03:19.026 --> 03:21.097
to just become
more self-sufficient.

03:21.131 --> 03:23.203
Everything gets used.

03:23.237 --> 03:27.379
Narrator:
Outside, Morgan prepares
a lure for baiting beaver.

03:27.414 --> 03:29.899
Morgan: I got these
beavers castors have dried here.

03:29.933 --> 03:32.177
Hopefully it will improve
my odds of getting a beaver

03:32.212 --> 03:35.939
to come to one of the traps
I plan on setting.

03:35.974 --> 03:39.115
Steep it in some oil
and tried to make a, you know,

03:39.149 --> 03:42.946
a paste that will smell
like beaver pheromone.

03:42.981 --> 03:47.330
And hopefully get another beaver
curious to come investigate.

03:47.365 --> 03:51.231
Beaver butter, that's about
what it should turn into it

03:51.265 --> 03:54.026
after it sits out here
a little while.

03:54.061 --> 03:55.752
You got lure?
Uh-huh,

03:55.787 --> 03:58.065
and other bait.

03:58.099 --> 03:59.549
Okay. Sounds good.

03:59.584 --> 04:01.206
I think
we're about ready to go.Yeah.

04:03.312 --> 04:06.901
The trails that we are choosing
for our trapline

04:06.936 --> 04:09.525
have to do with which species
we are targeting.

04:09.559 --> 04:11.975
With marten, they really like
black spruce forest,

04:12.010 --> 04:13.667
which is basically
all around us.

04:13.701 --> 04:15.807
You want to do something
with that old set?

04:15.841 --> 04:17.153
Yeah, that would be nice.

04:17.187 --> 04:19.604
The pole's already cut.

04:19.638 --> 04:21.606
Narrator: Morgan's failed to
make a catch with this snare

04:21.640 --> 04:23.401
since he set it last winter,

04:23.435 --> 04:26.058
but now he's adapting
his technique.

04:26.093 --> 04:28.751
We're still pretty new to this,
so we're trying to experiment

04:28.785 --> 04:33.100
and see what the animals
around here respond best to.

04:33.134 --> 04:35.896
So I'm gonna start putting some
boughs along the base.

04:35.930 --> 04:39.244
Are you just trying to keep it
from running up the main trunk?

04:39.279 --> 04:41.867
Do you want to encourage it
going up the pole as opposed

04:41.902 --> 04:44.042
to just straight up?

04:44.076 --> 04:48.115
We know basics about trapping,
so we're kind of continually

04:48.149 --> 04:49.496
building upon that.

04:49.530 --> 04:50.807
You know, we'll learn
through our mistakes.

04:50.842 --> 04:52.326
We'll learn through
our victories.

04:52.361 --> 04:55.329
I'm making a little catch
so that this trap

04:55.364 --> 04:56.986
will just kind of
set here.

04:57.020 --> 04:58.367
Morgan:
I'm gonna try something new

04:58.401 --> 05:01.301
by putting notches in the pole
to hold the trap

05:01.335 --> 05:02.647
so it's a little cleaner

05:02.681 --> 05:04.718
and you don't have to use
as much wire.

05:04.752 --> 05:06.858
Hey, you want to hang
that in there?

05:06.892 --> 05:08.618
Marten are incredibly
curious creatures,

05:08.653 --> 05:11.311
so you hang an attractant
in a visible way.

05:11.345 --> 05:14.314
Anything that is blowing
in the wind, like grouse wings.

05:14.348 --> 05:15.763
Then you can also
put bait on there.

05:15.798 --> 05:17.351
Is that
just blueberry jam?
Yeah.

05:17.386 --> 05:20.734
It's gonna be
irresistible.

05:20.768 --> 05:23.081
Let's get moving.

05:26.256 --> 05:29.259
♪♪

05:33.574 --> 05:36.612
Narrator: In North Carolina's
Blue Ridge Mountains,

05:36.646 --> 05:38.821
Eustace Conway
and Preston Roberts

05:38.855 --> 05:41.030
are on a mission
to salvage lost profits.

05:41.064 --> 05:43.895
Be nice to see what
we can come up with here.

05:43.929 --> 05:45.586
Yes, sir.

05:45.621 --> 05:46.898
They've spent
the last two weeks

05:46.932 --> 05:50.315
racing to stop a worm
infestation from spreading,

05:50.350 --> 05:52.938
but after hauling and milling
more than 100 logs

05:52.973 --> 05:55.182
from the stand
of storm-felled trees,

05:55.216 --> 05:57.805
they're claiming
an almost complete loss.

05:57.840 --> 06:00.670
Well, with wormholes in it,
nobody wants it.

06:00.705 --> 06:03.155
It's not worth
much of anything.

06:03.190 --> 06:05.951
It's inferior-grade
lumber.

06:05.986 --> 06:10.128
Nearly 80% of the recovered logs
are riddled with wormholes,

06:10.162 --> 06:12.717
damage that turns
a $500 tree

06:12.751 --> 06:15.651
into $75 worth of firewood

06:15.685 --> 06:18.205
unless you have the skills
of a craftsman.

06:18.239 --> 06:22.589
Wormy pine most easily is used
for paneling inside a house.

06:22.623 --> 06:25.177
If somebody wants a lot
of character on their walls,

06:25.212 --> 06:27.076
that's probably
the biggest market.

06:27.110 --> 06:30.217
And then there's other people
that might want a custom cabinet

06:30.251 --> 06:32.392
or a custom table made.

06:32.426 --> 06:34.911
Like, maybe
an old-timey farm table.

06:34.946 --> 06:37.673
Narrator:
If they can build enough
handmade wormy pine furniture,

06:37.707 --> 06:40.641
they should be able to recoup
some of their losses.

06:40.676 --> 06:43.610
But to be sure,
they'll need a prototype.

06:43.644 --> 06:45.819
Eustace: I don't know
if it will work or not.

06:45.853 --> 06:48.684
I just hope we can
at least break even here.

06:48.718 --> 06:51.203
Narrator: Today's project is
a rustic farm table.

06:51.238 --> 06:53.171
I guess
we'll build legs first.

06:53.205 --> 06:56.554
Let me grab us a 4x4
for that.

06:56.588 --> 06:59.039
One thing that Preston
and I both don't like

06:59.073 --> 07:00.385
about the modern world

07:00.420 --> 07:02.352
is everything
is just stamped out.

07:02.387 --> 07:03.802
It's just cookie cutter.

07:03.837 --> 07:07.461
32.

07:07.496 --> 07:09.808
But we're just gonna go
the extra mile

07:09.843 --> 07:14.295
and make it not just
your average table.

07:14.330 --> 07:17.920
We're making a tapered
cut on the legs, so in every way

07:17.954 --> 07:20.509
it's more graceful,
more beautiful.

07:20.543 --> 07:22.476
Narrator: To shape and build
the wood by hand,

07:22.511 --> 07:24.996
they use carpentry techniques
and tools

07:25.030 --> 07:27.343
that date
back hundreds of years.

07:29.379 --> 07:31.209
Eustace:
It's just sort of a step above

07:31.243 --> 07:34.143
what most things
are done nowadays.

07:34.177 --> 07:36.525
It's a challenge,
and that's why in this day

07:36.559 --> 07:40.529
and time I think
most people don't do it.

07:40.563 --> 07:42.116
That's a knot right there,
boy.

07:42.151 --> 07:43.497
That's hard to work through,
isn't it?

07:43.532 --> 07:46.466
I know where that saying,
"Tough as pine knot" comes from.

07:46.500 --> 07:48.398
[ Laughs ] Yeah,
you can see it right there.Right here.

07:48.433 --> 07:50.470
There it is.

07:50.504 --> 07:53.576
We want this table to last
for hundreds of years,

07:53.611 --> 07:56.337
not just a few.

07:56.372 --> 07:58.685
A lot of these old farm tables
are just square legs,

07:58.719 --> 08:00.583
square boards,
everything is kind of rough.

08:00.618 --> 08:03.137
But what we're doing
is taking a draw knife

08:03.172 --> 08:06.209
and just smoothing up the edges
and kind of rounding,

08:06.244 --> 08:09.523
softening things up to make it
look a little more elegant.

08:09.558 --> 08:12.492
And I think that value
could equate to more money.

08:12.526 --> 08:14.977
Yeah, looks all right.

08:15.011 --> 08:17.911
♪♪

08:20.810 --> 08:23.813
♪♪

08:26.678 --> 08:30.475
Narrator:
In Montana's Yaak Valley,
it's business as usual

08:30.510 --> 08:32.442
on Tom Oar's home trapline,

08:32.477 --> 08:34.859
the 30-mile loop
that he runs each day

08:34.893 --> 08:37.171
on the hunt
for marten and mink.

08:37.206 --> 08:41.313
But today, for the first time
in nearly 40 years,

08:41.348 --> 08:44.696
there's a new man
making the rounds.

08:44.731 --> 08:47.216
Sean: I think that my time
is best spent out here

08:47.250 --> 08:49.011
on this trapline doing things

08:49.045 --> 08:50.702
that take Tom away
from other things

08:50.737 --> 08:52.670
that he could be doing
back at his place.

08:52.704 --> 08:54.879
I was with him when
we first set these traps,

08:54.913 --> 08:56.501
so I know where all of them are,

08:56.536 --> 08:58.538
and I'm just moving through here
making sure everything is okay

08:58.572 --> 09:00.505
and looking
for marten signs as I go.

09:00.540 --> 09:03.025
Narrator: With 6 weeks of
apprenticeship under his belt,

09:03.059 --> 09:05.441
Sean is flying solo
for the first time,

09:05.475 --> 09:10.515
putting Tom's divide and conquer
strategy to the test.

09:10.550 --> 09:15.451
He's still got a lot to learn,
but he's starting to catch on.

09:15.485 --> 09:17.522
I've got some skinning to do,

09:17.557 --> 09:21.284
so he's running the marten line
that we've got out.

09:21.319 --> 09:24.149
So that's gonna free me up.

09:24.184 --> 09:26.704
Narrator: If the plan works,
it could double Tom's output

09:26.738 --> 09:28.326
for the season

09:28.360 --> 09:31.191
and help him stem the downturn
that has plagued his bottom line

09:31.225 --> 09:33.365
for more than 2 years.

09:33.400 --> 09:36.472
But it all depends
on whether Sean can deliver.

09:38.439 --> 09:41.615
Uh-oh.

09:41.650 --> 09:43.755
Huh.

09:43.790 --> 09:45.239
That's no good.

09:45.274 --> 09:47.656
The trap's all set off here.

09:47.690 --> 09:50.210
Something was messing
with it.

09:50.244 --> 09:51.798
So what we got here
is a marten set

09:51.832 --> 09:53.109
that's actually
been triggered.

09:53.144 --> 09:55.491
Doesn't appear to be
any kind of marten tracks,

09:55.525 --> 09:58.218
so probably just
a woodpecker or a bird.

09:58.252 --> 09:59.909
This is why you've got to check
your sets so often,

09:59.944 --> 10:02.532
to make sure that
they're functioning properly.

10:02.567 --> 10:05.570
♪♪

10:08.297 --> 10:10.851
Bait's still good.

10:10.886 --> 10:13.716
Get this thing re-oiled
and re-scented.

10:13.751 --> 10:15.960
Tom's a great teacher,
so to be able to learn

10:15.994 --> 10:18.376
some of these tricks of
the trapping trade in general,

10:18.410 --> 10:20.412
I'm just super, super grateful.

10:20.447 --> 10:22.414
All this stuff
is really valuable to me.

10:22.449 --> 10:24.140
Move on
and check some other ones,

10:24.175 --> 10:26.936
but this one looks all set now
and good to go.

10:29.007 --> 10:32.183
Narrator: The haul so far
this season has been modest.

10:32.217 --> 10:34.012
Sean needs a healthy trapline

10:34.047 --> 10:36.670
if he wants to help Tom
stay in the black.

10:36.705 --> 10:39.708
♪♪

10:44.540 --> 10:47.439
Oh, what do we have here?

10:47.474 --> 10:51.167
Wolf kill, for sure.

10:51.202 --> 10:53.376
Hmm.

10:53.411 --> 10:55.655
It wasn't last night,
but it's 48 hours.

10:55.689 --> 10:57.449
You can see there's
some snow on it.

10:59.762 --> 11:03.317
This looks like two
or three animals, I'm guessing.

11:03.352 --> 11:05.734
Tom's definitely gonna want
to see this.

11:05.768 --> 11:07.287
It is close enough
to the property

11:07.321 --> 11:09.185
where it's definitely a threat.

11:09.220 --> 11:12.499
Narrator:
A hungry pack of wolves less
than a mile from Tom's cabin

11:12.533 --> 11:16.641
puts the entire homestead
in danger.

11:16.676 --> 11:18.367
Sean: Being that
they didn't quite finish,

11:18.401 --> 11:20.438
they'll be back
to this kill to finish it up.

11:29.343 --> 11:31.173
O0 C1Narrator:
In the Yaak Valley,

11:31.207 --> 11:34.348
Sean has discovered an urgent
danger on the trapline

11:34.383 --> 11:38.318
less than a mile
from Tom's homestead.

11:38.352 --> 11:40.769
Hey! What are you doing back
already?

11:40.803 --> 11:42.909
Well, I've got something
you might want to see out there.

11:42.943 --> 11:46.015
There's wolves in here
the last day or two.
Yeah?

11:46.050 --> 11:47.879
They killed a deer
right there on line.A wolf kill?

11:47.914 --> 11:50.261
Pretty fresh, too.
Yeah.
Really?

11:50.295 --> 11:54.092
We could go take a look and kind
of assess the situation anyway.Yeah, yeah.

11:54.127 --> 11:56.577
Let me put this away,
and I'll be right there.

11:56.612 --> 11:59.408
Tom: We're so overwhelmed
with wolves.

11:59.442 --> 12:02.204
The Fish and Game says
there's five packs of them

12:02.238 --> 12:04.689
just here in the Yaak Valley.

12:04.724 --> 12:07.174
[ Engine starts ]

12:09.176 --> 12:12.283
Narrator:
The remote Northern Rockies
are prime wolf country.

12:12.317 --> 12:14.388
Living here requires
constant vigilance

12:14.423 --> 12:16.183
to keep predators at bay.

12:16.218 --> 12:19.221
♪♪

12:27.022 --> 12:29.300
Yeah, he's about all eaten up,
but not quite all the way.

12:29.334 --> 12:33.028
Wolves are a threat
to humans and animals.

12:33.062 --> 12:35.582
A single pack can have
more than six adults,

12:35.616 --> 12:39.310
each needing to devour more
than 10 pounds of meat per day.

12:39.344 --> 12:42.002
Tom: This is real close
to our house.

12:42.037 --> 12:43.970
One big pile of scat
there.

12:44.004 --> 12:47.836
Chances are they'll be
back to this site.

12:47.870 --> 12:49.182
Narrator: Tom's dog, Ellie,

12:49.216 --> 12:52.081
is particularly vulnerable
to attack.

12:52.116 --> 12:54.256
Tom: When Nancy walks the dog
every day,

12:54.290 --> 12:56.016
she carries bear spray

12:56.051 --> 12:58.674
just in case wolves
jump the dog.

12:58.708 --> 12:59.709
Wolves kill dogs.

12:59.744 --> 13:00.883
They love killing dogs.

13:00.918 --> 13:03.023
They love to eat dogs.

13:03.058 --> 13:05.060
♪♪

13:05.094 --> 13:07.683
These are the two
major trails here.
Yeah.

13:07.717 --> 13:11.652
If these wolves come back
into this kill,

13:11.687 --> 13:14.103
they'll walk right
in the same trails

13:14.138 --> 13:15.829
that they walked in before

13:15.864 --> 13:18.487
and that they left by
before.

13:18.521 --> 13:19.729
What are you thinking?

13:19.764 --> 13:22.836
Well, let's put traps
on these two trails.

13:22.871 --> 13:25.011
It's this close to the house
and everything, you know.

13:25.045 --> 13:26.736
Sure. Yeah.

13:26.771 --> 13:27.841
Let's go get traps.

13:27.876 --> 13:29.291
You got it, buddy.

13:29.325 --> 13:33.260
I don't want wolves eating
my dog or causing problems,

13:33.295 --> 13:36.470
so we're gonna have
to do something about it.

13:36.505 --> 13:39.508
♪♪

13:49.483 --> 13:50.726
Narrator: 400 miles south

13:50.760 --> 13:54.005
in Montana's rugged
Tobacco Root Mountains,

13:54.040 --> 13:57.043
Rich Lewis is gunning
for big game.

13:57.077 --> 13:59.666
Rich:
I came up here about 4 days ago.

13:59.700 --> 14:02.393
I only brought enough supplies
for about 5 days.

14:02.427 --> 14:05.568
If I don't bag an elk today,
that's it.

14:05.603 --> 14:08.675
I don't have much time left.

14:08.709 --> 14:12.334
Narrator:
After a relentless 6 straight
weeks of predator patrol,

14:12.368 --> 14:15.302
this is the first chance
he's had all season to hunt.

14:15.337 --> 14:17.857
Rich: I really need to stock up
on meat for the winter.

14:17.891 --> 14:21.170
When it's cold, the more protein
you have the warmer you stay.

14:21.205 --> 14:25.795
Narrator: Four days into
the hunt, he's finally on track.

14:25.830 --> 14:29.454
Rich: Elk track, right here.

14:29.489 --> 14:30.455
[ Whispering ]
I'm gonna take a look

14:30.490 --> 14:32.664
on the other
side of this ridge.

14:32.699 --> 14:37.048
Wind goes towards an elk,
he smells you, he's gone.

14:37.083 --> 14:39.533
But right now
the wind's coming perfect,

14:39.568 --> 14:43.917
so my plan is to get up
high enough above the elk

14:43.952 --> 14:47.058
so my scent
will go up away from the elk

14:47.093 --> 14:48.922
so they won't smell me.

14:48.957 --> 14:52.132
♪♪

14:52.167 --> 14:54.065
[ Normally ] Snow is really good
for tracking.

14:54.100 --> 14:56.930
You can see what the animals are
doing, which way they're going.

14:56.965 --> 14:58.759
You know,
where they're feeding.

14:58.794 --> 15:01.935
So you can maybe set up on them
and take them by surprise.

15:03.799 --> 15:06.077
Narrator: The temperature
is a frigid minus 10 degrees

15:06.112 --> 15:07.976
at this altitude,

15:08.010 --> 15:09.978
conditions that
are deteriorating

15:10.012 --> 15:12.187
as a storm front moves through.

15:14.534 --> 15:17.019
Man, it's getting cold.

15:22.093 --> 15:26.097
This storm, it's --
temperature's dropping big time.

15:26.132 --> 15:29.583
Narrator:
Rich has been exposed to
the cold for more than 3 hours.

15:29.618 --> 15:33.898
Rich: If the inside of your body
gets cold, hypothermia sets in.

15:33.933 --> 15:37.453
Boy, that means
you just go downhill fast.

15:37.488 --> 15:40.456
I just got to get warm.

15:40.491 --> 15:45.392
Narrator: A quick campfire helps
Rich prepare for the final push.

15:45.427 --> 15:47.567
He must close
in on the herd today

15:47.601 --> 15:50.570
or be forced to return home
empty-handed.

15:50.604 --> 15:54.091
[ Fire crackling ]

15:54.125 --> 15:56.265
Rich:
Fire's your only survival.

15:58.750 --> 16:00.338
[ Exhales sharply ]

16:00.373 --> 16:03.307
Fire is the most important thing
you've got right here.

16:03.341 --> 16:06.413
♪♪

16:14.870 --> 16:16.492
That storm is lifting...

16:19.495 --> 16:21.152
...and I'm finally warmed up
now.

16:25.294 --> 16:26.709
I've got a little time left.

16:26.744 --> 16:30.058
Hopefully I can still
get an elk.

16:30.092 --> 16:34.994
I'm going up on the ridgeline to
see if I can get a better view.

16:35.028 --> 16:38.618
If I don't get an elk,
I'm not sure what I'll do.

16:38.652 --> 16:41.207
I'm really counting on it
to make it through the winter.

16:41.241 --> 16:43.485
You know, when it gets
really cold like it is right now

16:43.519 --> 16:45.625
you need a lot of protein.

16:45.659 --> 16:48.662
♪♪

16:48.697 --> 16:53.184
All I can do is try to find
a track and keep looking.

16:53.219 --> 16:56.567
[ Whispering ]
Elk, right there. It's a cow.

16:56.601 --> 17:00.019
♪♪

17:12.548 --> 17:15.793
O0 C1Narrator: In Montana's
Tobacco Root Mountains,

17:15.827 --> 17:18.313
Rich finally has an elk herd
in his sights.

17:18.347 --> 17:22.524
♪♪

17:22.558 --> 17:24.215
Rich: Ah, they're running.

17:28.288 --> 17:31.015
♪♪

17:31.050 --> 17:33.535
I can't get a shot.

17:35.640 --> 17:36.952
No way I could have got
a shot at them

17:36.986 --> 17:39.575
through the trees like that.

17:39.610 --> 17:43.407
They were winding something up
on the side of the hill there,

17:43.441 --> 17:45.478
smelling something
in the air.

17:45.512 --> 17:48.895
So something out there
spooked them.

17:48.929 --> 17:50.345
I'm pretty sure
I got them figured out

17:50.379 --> 17:52.312
which way they're heading,
and I got to hustle down there.

17:52.347 --> 17:54.763
And I think I can
get them cut off,

17:54.797 --> 17:56.213
but I need to move quickly.

18:02.771 --> 18:04.911
These elk, they got spooked,
you know,

18:04.945 --> 18:07.016
and that's the only elk
that I seen.

18:10.917 --> 18:13.713
♪♪

18:13.747 --> 18:15.473
Wolf tracks, man.

18:15.508 --> 18:17.234
Narrator:
Herd animals instinctively bolt

18:17.268 --> 18:19.408
at the scent
of a nearby predator.

18:19.443 --> 18:21.962
Rich:
It's snowed in a little.

18:21.997 --> 18:23.757
That's a big wolf.

18:26.484 --> 18:29.418
They're everywhere.

18:29.453 --> 18:31.386
Right there,
here, here.

18:31.420 --> 18:33.698
Jumped over that log.

18:33.733 --> 18:36.701
These wolves are a disaster.

18:36.736 --> 18:39.532
They're really pushing
the elk out of here.

18:39.566 --> 18:42.845
They're just
a continuous problem.

18:42.880 --> 18:48.161
Narrator:
Wolves can run the elk at speeds
of up to 35 miles per hour.

18:48.196 --> 18:52.338
As daylight fades and the
temperature drops to minus 20,

18:52.372 --> 18:56.411
Rich doesn't stand a chance
of catching up.

18:56.445 --> 18:58.447
Rich: Well, I'm really
disappointed on this whole deal.

18:58.482 --> 19:00.035
I thought I'd come up here
and get an elk,

19:00.069 --> 19:01.657
and I'm just frustrated.

19:01.692 --> 19:04.039
I mean, you know, I don't know

19:04.073 --> 19:06.628
what I'm gonna do
for meat this year.

19:06.662 --> 19:10.321
My grocery store here is getting
harder to get food from.

19:10.356 --> 19:12.944
I mean, I got to figure some way
out to survive this winter

19:12.979 --> 19:14.567
because I'm about out of meat.

19:18.191 --> 19:21.160
♪♪

19:26.303 --> 19:29.340
Narrator:
The Blue Ridge Mountains have
long been home to men and women

19:29.375 --> 19:32.757
with the know-how to carve
a living from the land.

19:32.792 --> 19:35.139
Eustace and Preston are carrying
on the tradition,

19:35.174 --> 19:37.176
calling on
their mountain ingenuity

19:37.210 --> 19:40.938
to turn a setback
into an opportunity.

19:40.972 --> 19:42.353
You know,
you're getting ahead of me.

19:42.388 --> 19:45.149
Yeah, you know I want
to see this thing done.

19:45.184 --> 19:47.531
If their hand-crafted
raw wood farm table

19:47.565 --> 19:49.567
can fetch a fair price
at market,

19:49.602 --> 19:50.913
they could reclaim some value

19:50.948 --> 19:52.639
from the hundreds
of worm-bitten board

19:52.674 --> 19:55.504
that they'll otherwise
have to toss as scrap.

19:55.539 --> 19:57.610
We're making really
good headway on this table.

19:57.644 --> 19:59.267
So we've made the legs,

19:59.301 --> 20:02.270
and we've put the horizontal
skirt all the way around.

20:02.304 --> 20:04.789
It kind of ties it together.

20:04.824 --> 20:07.689
Now we're figuring it out.

20:07.723 --> 20:10.105
Preston: You know,
we're doing it all by hand.

20:10.139 --> 20:13.177
It's a lot of work,
but it's gonna be solid.

20:13.212 --> 20:15.455
About here, isn't it?Yeah.

20:15.490 --> 20:18.078
Those wormholes don't look
half bad, do they?

20:18.113 --> 20:20.011
I think those wormholes look
real good.

20:20.046 --> 20:21.012
Yeah.

20:21.047 --> 20:23.843
Eustace:
So we've got the tabletop shaped

20:23.877 --> 20:26.501
where it's ready
to go on top of the frame.

20:26.535 --> 20:28.434
Narrator:
19th century square-cut nails

20:28.468 --> 20:30.712
will secure the pieces
together.

20:30.746 --> 20:33.266
Individually hand-forged
from solid steel,

20:33.301 --> 20:34.785
they're stronger
and more durable

20:34.819 --> 20:36.856
than anything
you can buy in a store.

20:36.890 --> 20:38.720
Eustace: They're actually
a superior nail.

20:38.754 --> 20:41.757
The square-cut nail
has a lot more surface area

20:41.792 --> 20:43.759
than a round wire nail,

20:43.794 --> 20:45.830
and they'll hold really well.

20:45.865 --> 20:47.625
We're basically using

20:47.660 --> 20:51.284
every old-timey
kind of design technique we can

20:51.319 --> 20:54.356
to make it as strong
as a table can be built.

20:54.391 --> 20:56.220
It's nice, isn't it?

20:56.255 --> 20:58.153
Yeah, this is nice,

20:58.187 --> 21:02.053
but I'm not sure
that's long enough.

21:02.088 --> 21:04.401
I think that's everything
that we've got,

21:04.435 --> 21:07.818
just that size.

21:07.852 --> 21:11.270
Need to be about half an inch
longer than that, really.

21:11.304 --> 21:13.686
It's just not reaching,
is it?

21:13.720 --> 21:15.895
I can heat these
up and draw them out,

21:15.929 --> 21:16.930
make a longer nail.

21:16.965 --> 21:19.243
I can draw every one out
if we have to.

21:19.278 --> 21:20.313
Sure.

21:22.626 --> 21:24.662
Narrator: Heating the steel
to 1,500 degrees

21:24.697 --> 21:27.734
makes it malleable enough
to shape and stretch.

21:27.769 --> 21:30.289
Preston:
A lot of irons in the fire.

21:33.395 --> 21:36.260
I got one ready.Okay.

21:36.295 --> 21:39.574
Eustace:
It's a matter of getting it hot,
which makes it soft,

21:39.608 --> 21:42.991
and then hitting it
with a cross pein hammer

21:43.025 --> 21:46.443
to push it out
and make it longer.

21:46.477 --> 21:48.479
♪♪

21:48.514 --> 21:50.412
That's
what we're looking for.

21:58.247 --> 22:01.216
That's
what I'm talking about.Yeah.

22:01.250 --> 22:02.769
We want this table to last,

22:02.804 --> 22:08.430
so that somebody can enjoy it
for generation after generation.

22:08.465 --> 22:09.673
They look good, don't they?

22:09.707 --> 22:12.607
I think it's about ready
for the oil here, Preston.

22:12.641 --> 22:16.369
♪♪

22:16.404 --> 22:18.820
Filling those wormholes up.[ Chuckles ]

22:18.854 --> 22:20.891
Just soaking it up.

22:20.925 --> 22:23.307
Preston: Wood's porous.

22:23.342 --> 22:25.965
If we just leave it, you know,
just like it is,

22:25.999 --> 22:27.380
the moisture in the air

22:27.415 --> 22:29.831
is gonna cause
that board to swell.

22:29.865 --> 22:33.731
And we can alleviate a lot
of that problem with oils.

22:35.526 --> 22:37.873
Oh, yeah.

22:37.908 --> 22:41.256
Eustace:
All the time that we were
pulling out all this wormy pine,

22:41.290 --> 22:43.189
I was really wondering
if it's gonna be worth it.

22:43.223 --> 22:46.330
And I just kept thinking
somehow we can make this work.

22:46.365 --> 22:47.849
Somehow, we can use this.

22:47.883 --> 22:51.922
I'm gonna go get the -- the
truck and bring it over here.

22:51.956 --> 22:53.682
And we'll load it up.

22:53.717 --> 22:56.271
I think we've got it
polished down good enough.

22:56.305 --> 22:58.377
Narrator: With
the finished product complete,

22:58.411 --> 23:00.724
they'll haul it to town
to gets it value appraised

23:00.758 --> 23:04.521
and determine what kind of
market their might be for more.

23:04.555 --> 23:07.558
[ Exhales ]

23:07.593 --> 23:10.147
Preston:
It's a lot of work getting
this thing out of the woods,

23:10.181 --> 23:11.320
you know,
and making it,

23:11.355 --> 23:14.945
and we've got
a lot of labor involved.

23:14.979 --> 23:17.050
So my hope is that
when we go to town

23:17.085 --> 23:18.362
that we'll get
some good news.

23:18.397 --> 23:19.950
That he'll look at it
and be impressed,

23:19.984 --> 23:21.917
and like what we're doing,
you know,

23:21.952 --> 23:24.437
and give us
a good number for it.

23:24.472 --> 23:27.578
And then we'll see if
we're not gonna be okay.

23:31.271 --> 23:34.274
♪♪

23:38.347 --> 23:41.350
Narrator:
In the Ozark Mountains,

23:41.385 --> 23:44.215
Jason Hawk is working
to get back on his feet

23:44.250 --> 23:46.459
after a series of unexpected
events forced him

23:46.494 --> 23:50.325
to sell his homestead.

23:50.359 --> 23:52.879
Jason: Wound up losing my dad
in the summer,

23:52.914 --> 23:56.745
losing him,
losing the place.

23:56.780 --> 23:58.920
There are some really
good years in your life,

23:58.954 --> 24:01.301
and there are
those years that just...

24:01.336 --> 24:03.994
they just lay you flat.

24:04.028 --> 24:07.066
And we're digging out
of one of those.

24:07.100 --> 24:10.172
Narrator:
The Hawks are living in a canvas
camp on a friend's property

24:10.207 --> 24:13.210
while they're hunting
for new land to call home.

24:13.244 --> 24:14.867
After 3 months of searching,

24:14.901 --> 24:17.456
they have yet to find
a suitable property.

24:20.113 --> 24:22.875
Hey, how'd it go?

24:22.909 --> 24:25.429
Not great.
[ Sighs ]

24:27.673 --> 24:30.745
That place is just
not gonna work.

24:30.779 --> 24:34.507
Mary: It's so hard for me
to see how frustrated he gets.

24:34.542 --> 24:38.097
I know how much he wants us
to be comfortable and good,

24:38.131 --> 24:40.617
and it really weighs on him.

24:40.651 --> 24:42.411
Narrator:
Despite the slow progress,

24:42.446 --> 24:45.553
the family is determined
to make their life here,

24:45.587 --> 24:47.969
where survival
requires hard work

24:48.003 --> 24:50.005
and constant attention.

24:50.040 --> 24:53.561
Hate to suggest a shift
in priorities,

24:53.595 --> 24:56.667
but we're getting
pretty low on meat supply.

24:56.702 --> 24:58.531
Yeah, I saw that.

24:58.566 --> 25:01.292
We're sitting in the middle
of hog country.

25:01.327 --> 25:02.811
We target the hogs.

25:02.846 --> 25:06.781
I think the best thing
to do is -- is trap.

25:06.815 --> 25:09.922
Jason: The real advantage,
trapping versus hunting,

25:09.956 --> 25:12.027
it's the most efficient
use of time.

25:12.062 --> 25:14.305
If I'm out hunting,
I'm not doing other things,

25:14.340 --> 25:17.688
whereas a trap,
you set, go back to work.

25:17.723 --> 25:19.621
If you're living
my lifestyle right now,

25:19.656 --> 25:22.866
that's exactly what I need.

25:22.900 --> 25:25.627
I say scout around, find a place
and then come up

25:25.662 --> 25:27.871
with just some kind of trap
to hold them.

25:27.905 --> 25:30.218
Sounds like a plan.

25:30.252 --> 25:31.978
I'm gonna catch you
after a bit, babe.

25:32.013 --> 25:33.324
All right.

25:33.359 --> 25:37.225
Narrator: The Ozark wilderness
is overrun by feral hogs,

25:37.259 --> 25:40.297
but trapping one
won't be easy.

25:40.331 --> 25:43.956
They're highly intelligent
and wary of humans.

25:43.990 --> 25:47.131
♪♪

25:49.168 --> 25:52.033
Jason: They're gonna be after
what's left over of the acorns

25:52.067 --> 25:54.518
and the walnuts
this time of year,

25:54.553 --> 25:57.107
so best bet start downing some
of the little haulers,

25:57.141 --> 25:59.592
little oak flats,
see what we can find.

26:01.939 --> 26:04.459
Little bit torn up
in through here.

26:06.875 --> 26:09.395
That sign, there.

26:11.535 --> 26:14.262
They get lice,
and so they'll rub in the mud,

26:14.296 --> 26:16.713
and then they'll come out
and let it dry

26:16.747 --> 26:18.542
and they'll rub up
against trees.

26:18.577 --> 26:21.303
Like a big ol' back scratcher
for them.

26:21.338 --> 26:22.650
That's relatively fresh.

26:22.684 --> 26:25.687
It's not completely dried out.

26:25.722 --> 26:27.724
That's some good looking sign.

26:33.764 --> 26:35.076
Look right here.

26:38.320 --> 26:40.219
This is what I want to see.

26:40.253 --> 26:44.154
You see this little areas that
are pulled up in through here?

26:44.188 --> 26:45.431
That's rooting.

26:45.465 --> 26:46.915
That's where they get down
with their nose.

26:46.950 --> 26:50.609
They're trying to get either
the acorns or the black walnuts.

26:50.643 --> 26:53.059
This is definitely hogs
in through here.

26:53.094 --> 26:55.027
And the funniest thing
about it is

26:55.061 --> 26:57.961
this is maybe 50 yards
from the camp,

26:57.995 --> 27:00.032
so this is gonna be
easy to check,

27:00.066 --> 27:02.137
not that far to haul materials,

27:02.172 --> 27:03.622
and the other
beautiful thing about it

27:03.656 --> 27:05.451
is I should be able
to hear them.

27:13.390 --> 27:18.084
Narrator: In a remote hollow
of the Ozark Mountains...

27:18.119 --> 27:21.916
Well,
we're right down here.

27:21.950 --> 27:23.469
...Jason and Mary
are getting to work

27:23.503 --> 27:26.161
securing their next meal.

27:26.196 --> 27:29.337
So what I'm thinking...
[ Grunts ]

27:29.371 --> 27:35.067
...an idea is
if we could hinge this,

27:35.101 --> 27:37.448
that could be the gate.

27:37.483 --> 27:40.451
They've scavenged materials from
a scrap pile on the property

27:40.486 --> 27:44.248
which they'll use to engineer
an improvised hog trap.

27:44.283 --> 27:45.733
Like a one-way?

27:45.767 --> 27:48.701
So they're pushing in, but when
they try to get back they...

27:48.736 --> 27:51.670
When they try to push out,
yeah.Okay. I'm following.

27:54.327 --> 27:57.710
Narrator:
Metal stakes and wire fencing
make a 10-foot perimeter.

27:59.712 --> 28:01.818
All right.
That will do it.

28:01.852 --> 28:04.337
But the key to the design
is a pulley system

28:04.372 --> 28:07.720
to activate the trap door.

28:07.755 --> 28:10.171
Now comes the fun part --
setting up the trigger for it.

28:10.205 --> 28:13.519
The trigger system for this is
just gonna be a simple toggle

28:13.553 --> 28:16.280
and a little ground tie
braced off of a nail,

28:16.315 --> 28:18.662
so when they hit a trip wire
rooting around

28:18.697 --> 28:20.146
in there picking up feed,

28:20.181 --> 28:23.667
it will snap the trap
down behind them.

28:23.702 --> 28:25.358
All right.
You at a safe distance?

28:25.393 --> 28:26.739
I'm out of the way.

28:26.774 --> 28:27.982
You ready?
Yeah.

28:28.016 --> 28:30.950
♪♪

28:30.985 --> 28:32.089
There we go.

28:32.124 --> 28:33.884
Ha-ha!

28:33.919 --> 28:36.335
All right.
We got this set.

28:36.369 --> 28:38.544
I think it's time
for some bait.

28:38.578 --> 28:40.442
You can use just about
anything for bait.

28:40.477 --> 28:42.617
In this case,
I'm using some corn.

28:45.206 --> 28:46.932
Every last little bit.

28:48.968 --> 28:50.694
We've done
all the work we can.

28:50.729 --> 28:52.765
Now it's just time
to let it soak,

28:52.800 --> 28:54.215
and hopefully it will
do its job.

28:54.249 --> 28:56.769
All right.
Let the trap do its work.

28:56.804 --> 28:58.219
That's it.

28:58.253 --> 28:59.738
The longer you're here,
the more scent you're leaving.

29:02.637 --> 29:05.709
♪♪

29:09.333 --> 29:12.440
Narrator:
A storm front blowing across
the Great Alaska Range

29:12.474 --> 29:14.235
is adding a fresh layer of snow

29:14.269 --> 29:17.410
to the 2-foot deep pack
already on the ground.

29:17.445 --> 29:20.724
But Morgan and Margaret
are not deterred by the weather.

29:20.759 --> 29:22.830
They're pushing ahead
on the hunt for good ground

29:22.864 --> 29:24.383
to lay traps.

29:24.417 --> 29:26.592
doubling down on their
potential catch

29:26.626 --> 29:30.907
by targeting different
types of game.

29:30.941 --> 29:32.529
It doesn't really make
that much sense for us

29:32.563 --> 29:34.738
to set traps together,
so we're gonna split up.

29:34.773 --> 29:36.740
And we can cover
more territory that way,

29:36.775 --> 29:38.466
just to make sure
that we are spreading

29:38.500 --> 29:40.744
our impact out
as much as possible.

29:40.779 --> 29:43.678
Narrator:
Margaret heads into the woods
to make a marten set,

29:43.712 --> 29:45.128
while Morgan searches for signs

29:45.162 --> 29:48.200
of beaver activity
along the frozen waterways.

29:48.234 --> 29:50.754
There's a lot of brush down here
and a lot of water,

29:50.789 --> 29:52.411
so seems like
the kind of place

29:52.445 --> 29:55.276
where a beaver might want
to build a dam.

29:55.310 --> 29:57.968
Narrator:
During the winter months,
beavers stay active beneath

29:58.003 --> 30:00.212
the iced-over lakes and ponds,

30:00.246 --> 30:02.214
where their prized
fur insulates them

30:02.248 --> 30:03.940
from the frigid water.

30:08.876 --> 30:10.912
Morgan: Oh, nice.

30:10.947 --> 30:14.467
I just broke through
with my snow shoe.

30:14.502 --> 30:18.057
Here's a freshly-chewed
beaver chew there,

30:18.092 --> 30:21.820
so looks like I might be
getting close to a beaver pond.

30:25.513 --> 30:26.617
There we go.

30:26.652 --> 30:27.929
There's the lodge.

30:27.964 --> 30:28.861
There's a big dam.

30:28.896 --> 30:30.656
It seems like an active area.

30:30.690 --> 30:32.313
I'm gonna try
to find a good spot

30:32.347 --> 30:34.349
to cut a hole in the ice.

30:34.384 --> 30:35.972
Narrator:
To set a proper trap,

30:36.006 --> 30:39.838
he needs to reach free-flowing
water below the ice sheet.

30:39.872 --> 30:42.150
Morgan: There is a beaver lodge,
for sure.

30:42.185 --> 30:44.463
Probably water underneath
right here.

30:44.497 --> 30:47.466
Just try to clear away
some of this snow here.

30:47.500 --> 30:50.814
Narrator:
But with a dense blanket of
snow covering the entire creek,

30:50.849 --> 30:53.748
it's impossible to know
exactly where to dig.

30:55.784 --> 30:57.510
Morgan: I'm gonna cut
through this ice,

30:57.545 --> 31:00.341
lower a lure trap
in through the hole.

31:00.375 --> 31:03.378
♪♪

31:22.190 --> 31:25.193
I don't know about this.

31:25.228 --> 31:28.507
I think that's just,
like, solid overflow ice.

31:28.541 --> 31:31.786
All the way down
to the old snow layer.

31:31.820 --> 31:33.443
What looks like the open water

31:33.477 --> 31:35.928
just keeps getting further
and further away.

31:35.963 --> 31:37.930
You know, at first it looked it
like the ice

31:37.965 --> 31:39.138
was only 4 inches thick,

31:39.173 --> 31:40.829
and then it looked like it
was 6 inches thick,

31:40.864 --> 31:42.555
and then it was 8 inches thick.

31:42.590 --> 31:44.799
And it didn't look like
I was getting anywhere.

31:44.833 --> 31:46.145
I think that's just solid ice.

31:46.180 --> 31:50.805
I think I could keep chiseling
a hole down for 3 feet.

31:50.839 --> 31:52.772
I just wasted
a bunch of time.

31:52.807 --> 31:55.258
I guess I'll just have
to keep looking.

31:59.883 --> 32:02.437
Narrator: ComingNarrator: In Alaska,

32:02.472 --> 32:06.821
Morgan's discovered an
ideal spot to hunt for beaver,

32:06.855 --> 32:10.273
but so far the winter
is locking him out.

32:10.307 --> 32:13.414
We had some real cold weather
this fall.

32:13.448 --> 32:18.971
It may have frozen up the ice
real thick around here.

32:19.006 --> 32:21.284
Narrator: Thick ice and dense
snow pack make it difficult

32:21.318 --> 32:23.665
to determine
the depth of the creek

32:23.700 --> 32:26.772
and break through
to the flowing water below.

32:26.806 --> 32:28.636
Morgan: See here where
the ice collapsed?

32:28.670 --> 32:31.018
Especially over there
on the high side.

32:31.052 --> 32:32.881
So there's got to be
an opening or a crack

32:32.916 --> 32:35.263
of some kind here
underneath the ice.

32:35.298 --> 32:37.645
I see a place where the ice
is collapsed.

32:37.679 --> 32:39.854
Usually there's a nice space
underneath there

32:39.888 --> 32:42.270
where animals are moving back
and forth.

32:42.305 --> 32:45.239
♪♪

32:57.423 --> 32:59.632
Yeah, this is good.

32:59.667 --> 33:03.533
That's just deep enough
to get a trap into

33:03.567 --> 33:06.605
and to have
a beaver travel through.

33:06.639 --> 33:08.331
Oh, cool, finally.

33:08.365 --> 33:10.402
You could see there was air
underneath there,

33:10.436 --> 33:13.853
and I'm sure that critters are
using it as a little pathway.

33:13.888 --> 33:16.925
I'm gonna try to get a trap
in here before it gets too dark.

33:21.723 --> 33:24.554
The last step is to get
a little of that beaver lure

33:24.588 --> 33:26.832
on there that I made up.

33:26.866 --> 33:30.870
Narrator:
Beaver castor gland oil is
a time-tested trapper strategy,

33:30.905 --> 33:34.633
but in this harsh environment
the rest may depend on luck.

33:34.667 --> 33:39.569
Morgan:
Get this in there and stick
it up underneath the ice there.

33:39.603 --> 33:41.743
Real gentle here.

33:41.778 --> 33:42.572
All right.

33:42.606 --> 33:45.023
I think that will work.

33:45.057 --> 33:47.301
First one of the season.

33:47.335 --> 33:49.717
A lot of time
just finding one spot.

33:49.751 --> 33:50.994
I got to get moving.

33:51.029 --> 33:54.653
I know Margaret's
waiting for me.

33:54.687 --> 33:58.036
I've got some trail cut
and some new country explored.

33:58.070 --> 34:01.177
We pushed our trapline a little
further, so we'll be back at it

34:01.211 --> 34:03.351
and hopefully
we'll catch something.

34:06.113 --> 34:09.116
♪♪

34:12.671 --> 34:14.949
Narrator:
In the Northern Rockies,

34:14.983 --> 34:17.779
man has battled wolf
for thousands of years.

34:17.814 --> 34:20.610
And today, with the predator's
numbers on the rebound,

34:20.644 --> 34:21.714
those who live in the mountains

34:21.749 --> 34:23.889
must operate
with extreme caution.

34:23.923 --> 34:25.511
All right.

34:25.546 --> 34:29.619
A wolf pack active on Tom's
property is a serious threat.

34:29.653 --> 34:32.484
He holds a special license
from the State of Montana

34:32.518 --> 34:34.831
that allows him
to trap wolves on his property

34:34.865 --> 34:37.489
to help protect
against their growing numbers.

34:37.523 --> 34:40.008
Let's put up two sets.

34:40.043 --> 34:41.458
There's gloves for you.

34:41.493 --> 34:44.634
I got gloves here.

34:44.668 --> 34:45.876
A wolf's sense of smell

34:45.911 --> 34:48.914
is 100 times
more sensitive than a human's.

34:48.948 --> 34:50.364
They need to take
every precaution

34:50.398 --> 34:52.366
to cover their tracks.

34:52.400 --> 34:54.126
Tom: We always want
to wear clean gloves

34:54.161 --> 34:57.440
when you're handling
our equipment.

34:57.474 --> 35:00.650
Any odor that you leave behind
will make them so suspicious

35:00.684 --> 35:03.963
you probably
will never catch one.

35:03.998 --> 35:06.311
These have all been
dyed and waxed.

35:06.345 --> 35:08.244
These are all odor-free traps.

35:08.278 --> 35:10.487
We want them
completely scentless,

35:10.522 --> 35:12.455
so that wolf,
when he comes along

35:12.489 --> 35:13.697
he ain't got no idea

35:13.732 --> 35:15.734
there's a trap buried
in the snow.

35:15.768 --> 35:18.530
Narrator: A plastic bag masks
any remaining scent,

35:18.564 --> 35:19.669
and prevents snow and ice

35:19.703 --> 35:22.189
from building up
on the trigger mechanism.

35:22.223 --> 35:24.363
Wolf trapping
is very exciting.

35:24.398 --> 35:28.298
Even just setting the trap
and putting it in your basket

35:28.333 --> 35:30.162
before you even take it
to the place

35:30.197 --> 35:32.164
where you gonna set it.

35:32.199 --> 35:33.752
Sean:
This is where trust comes.

35:33.786 --> 35:35.409
Yeah, really.

35:35.443 --> 35:38.066
Wolves are such
a tricky animal to trap.

35:38.101 --> 35:39.413
Wolves are.
No doubt about it.

35:39.447 --> 35:42.278
They kind of put you to the test
when it comes to trapping.

35:42.312 --> 35:46.592
To be able to trap a gray wolf
is an amazing accomplishment.

35:48.767 --> 35:50.941
Narrator: Wolves are known
to return to a kill site

35:50.976 --> 35:53.323
until the carcass
is stripped clean.

35:53.358 --> 35:54.945
You see that little tree?

35:54.980 --> 35:55.946
Yep.

35:55.981 --> 35:57.224
That trail runs
right next to there.

35:57.258 --> 35:59.157
I'm gonna go
right out through here.

35:59.191 --> 36:00.537
Maybe what I'll do is
I'll go all the way

36:00.572 --> 36:01.780
around the back side,

36:01.814 --> 36:04.265
find that second trail
over there.
Yeah. Yeah.

36:04.300 --> 36:07.717
So we won't have any scent
inside the two trails, you know.

36:07.751 --> 36:09.719
Perfect.
Sounds good, mister.

36:12.308 --> 36:15.518
Tom: You don't walk down
the trail that the wolf made.

36:15.552 --> 36:17.899
You come in from the side,

36:17.934 --> 36:20.902
and then you stop
before you get to the trail.

36:20.937 --> 36:25.459
Then you bust a hole in
the snow underneath the trail,

36:25.493 --> 36:28.979
and slide your trap
into the wolf track

36:29.014 --> 36:30.567
that is in the trail.

36:30.602 --> 36:33.605
And then you sift a little
snow over your trap

36:33.639 --> 36:35.503
so you can't see it.

36:35.538 --> 36:37.436
It's all buried in there.

36:37.471 --> 36:43.062
To beat something that
sophisticated at its own game,

36:43.097 --> 36:44.788
that's what it's all about.

36:44.823 --> 36:47.205
How are you doing, Sean?Good.

36:47.239 --> 36:49.034
I just about got it,
actually.

36:49.068 --> 36:50.138
Yeah.

36:50.173 --> 36:53.107
That's one of
the big things about it.

36:53.141 --> 36:55.213
You want to get in there
and out real fast.

36:55.247 --> 36:56.697
Yeah.

36:56.731 --> 36:58.146
Meet you
at the snowmobiles.
Okay.

36:58.181 --> 37:00.183
I'm gonna go back out
the way I came in then.

37:00.218 --> 37:03.290
To make that wolf step
into something

37:03.324 --> 37:06.845
when he's got thousands
of acres to run in.

37:06.879 --> 37:08.985
Make that wolf step in there,
you got him,

37:09.019 --> 37:10.573
it will make you feel good.

37:15.785 --> 37:17.511
Narrator: In North Carolina,

37:17.545 --> 37:21.273
Eustace and Preston are making
a rare journey to town

37:21.308 --> 37:26.105
on a mission
to turn trash into treasure.

37:26.140 --> 37:28.384
They have hand-crafted
a piece of specialty furniture

37:28.418 --> 37:31.214
from wormy pine,

37:31.249 --> 37:32.698
and are here to
consult an expert

37:32.733 --> 37:35.494
to find out if it will sell.

37:35.529 --> 37:36.495
Eustace:
What do you say, Gary?

37:36.530 --> 37:37.945
-Hey.
-How are you guys doing?

37:37.979 --> 37:39.740
Doing great.
Good to see you.

37:39.774 --> 37:41.949
Narrator: If they can reclaim
enough of the lumber's value

37:41.983 --> 37:43.502
with this prototype,

37:43.537 --> 37:46.091
it could open up
a new business opportunity.

37:46.125 --> 37:47.644
We're over at Boone Custom.

37:47.679 --> 37:49.957
My friend Gary
runs this place,

37:49.991 --> 37:52.097
and, uh, I figured
he would be able to tell us

37:52.131 --> 37:53.340
what the table is worth

37:53.374 --> 37:56.964
because he works
with this stuff every day.

37:56.998 --> 37:58.483
I don't know
what he's gonna say.

37:58.517 --> 38:00.416
I don't know how much
the table is worth,

38:00.450 --> 38:03.350
so all I can be is hopeful
and a little nervous

38:03.384 --> 38:06.560
he might not make it
valuable enough to be doing it.

38:06.594 --> 38:10.080
Narrator: The table must
appraise for at least $600

38:10.115 --> 38:12.117
if Eustace and Preston
are going to break even

38:12.151 --> 38:14.395
on materials and labor.

38:14.430 --> 38:18.330
Typically when you see
wormholes in the wood,

38:18.365 --> 38:21.644
that's normally something people
would shy away from

38:21.678 --> 38:25.268
and they wouldn't
want to buy that.

38:25.303 --> 38:27.166
But, uh, right now,

38:27.201 --> 38:30.066
it's becoming quite popular
and trendy.

38:30.100 --> 38:34.346
20 years ago, American market
wanted things new.

38:34.381 --> 38:38.626
And now reclaimed products
are very trendy.

38:38.661 --> 38:42.665
Something like this could
easily sell for 3,500 bucks.

38:42.699 --> 38:44.425
No way.
I believe you could
get $3,500 for it.

38:44.460 --> 38:45.978
-Whoo-hoo!
-Yeah.

38:46.013 --> 38:47.808
Oh, my God!

38:47.842 --> 38:48.671
I'm loving it.

38:48.705 --> 38:50.362
I mean, this makes it worth it.

38:50.397 --> 38:52.468
That makes knocking
that rock off,

38:52.502 --> 38:53.917
you know, fixing the road,

38:53.952 --> 38:55.712
pulling out all this
wormy pine...

38:55.747 --> 38:58.577
This is gonna actually
come around and pay it off.

38:58.612 --> 39:03.133
Coffee tables, end tables,
the whole line of Legacy tables.

39:03.168 --> 39:04.652
Yeah![ Laughs ]

39:04.687 --> 39:07.655
Now that we know that this stuff
is as valuable as it is,

39:07.690 --> 39:10.209
we've got work to do
and money to make.

39:10.244 --> 39:12.004
[ Chuckles ] Love it.

39:14.628 --> 39:17.631
♪♪

39:22.256 --> 39:25.984
Narrator:
It's family dinner time
in the Ozark back country.

39:26.018 --> 39:28.538
-How was your day?
-Good.

39:28.573 --> 39:30.540
Mary:
Anything fun happen?

39:30.575 --> 39:31.783
Lunch.

39:31.817 --> 39:34.993
Lunch? [ Laughs ][ Chuckles ]

39:35.027 --> 39:37.271
Narrator:
With only two days of protein
left in the larder,

39:37.305 --> 39:40.136
the Hawks
are counting on a win.

39:40.170 --> 39:41.379
Oh, I'm tired.

39:41.413 --> 39:44.105
Daddy and I built
a hog trap today.

39:44.140 --> 39:46.073
Do you think
we're gonna catch anything?

39:46.107 --> 39:49.594
Uh-huh. Bacon![ Laughs ]

39:49.628 --> 39:51.112
Oh, I hope so.

39:51.147 --> 39:53.391
It's nice to have some
relaxing time with family,

39:53.425 --> 39:54.806
but not having a full larder,

39:54.840 --> 39:56.635
there's always that thing
in the back of your head.

39:56.670 --> 39:59.500
It's like an unpaid bill
sitting there.

39:59.535 --> 40:01.571
-Um, Mom?
-Mm-hmm?

40:01.606 --> 40:04.194
Would it be okay if I...Shh. Shh.

40:04.229 --> 40:06.127
[ Rustling ]

40:06.162 --> 40:07.750
There's no way.

40:14.619 --> 40:15.965
I'm gonna go take
a walk down there.

40:19.969 --> 40:21.004
-Dad?
-Yeah?

40:21.039 --> 40:22.627
-Can I come?
-No, baby.

40:22.661 --> 40:25.181
It's getting dark.
-Okay.

40:25.215 --> 40:28.184
-I'll be back in a bit.
-All right. Good luck.

40:28.218 --> 40:30.566
Jason:
It may just be a deer moving
around through the bottom,

40:30.600 --> 40:32.602
or maybe it just the wind,

40:32.637 --> 40:34.949
but might as well
check the trap anyway.

40:37.676 --> 40:40.438
I don't see anything.

40:40.472 --> 40:42.785
Looks like the trap
is down though.

40:42.819 --> 40:44.614
Son of a bitch.

40:44.649 --> 40:48.791
♪♪

40:48.825 --> 40:51.276
Damn pig come
under the fence.

40:54.797 --> 40:56.212
Damn it.

40:56.246 --> 40:59.353
At this point, the only thing
I know is go after this pig.

40:59.387 --> 41:02.563
But if the trap and digging out
didn't spook him enough,

41:02.598 --> 41:06.774
me tromping right
behind him is going to.

41:06.809 --> 41:09.190
Chances are better I'll see
tracks in the morning.

41:09.225 --> 41:12.677
Me and Mary, more than a
full day's work for two people.

41:12.711 --> 41:15.231
We're still none the closer.

41:15.265 --> 41:17.889
No meat on the ground.

41:17.923 --> 41:22.514
It just seems like
nothing's panning out.

41:22.549 --> 41:25.034
Hell of a day.

41:29.279 --> 41:33.145
Narrator:
Next time on "Mountain Men"...

41:33.180 --> 41:35.872
the wolves are closing in...

41:35.907 --> 41:37.805
All right.
We can kind of see

41:37.840 --> 41:39.566
the scene of the crime here.

41:39.600 --> 41:41.706
A wolf kill is like
a dinner bell

41:41.740 --> 41:43.742
for all the predators, really.

41:43.777 --> 41:47.297
So you have an opportunity
to catch a decent amount of fur.

41:47.332 --> 41:49.748
Narrator:
...Jason goes full bore...

41:49.783 --> 41:51.232
Jason: We got about 2 more days
worth of meat,

41:51.267 --> 41:54.028
so today there is
only one priority.

41:54.063 --> 41:55.202
Let's hunt this pig.

41:55.236 --> 41:57.238
Narrator:
...to provide for his family...

41:57.273 --> 41:58.170
Jason: Get that head around.

41:58.205 --> 41:59.827
[ Gunshot fires ]

41:59.862 --> 42:01.829
Narrator:
...and Morgan takes a hit.

42:01.864 --> 42:05.246
[ Groans ]
[ Bleep ] Damn it.

42:05.281 --> 42:06.524
I knocked that thing
into my leg.

42:06.558 --> 42:09.872
Yeah, there's, uh,
blood running down my leg.

42:09.906 --> 42:10.838
Margaret!

42:10.873 --> 42:12.115
-Ooh, that's pretty bad.
-Yeah.

42:12.150 --> 42:15.429
♪♪
